Scrum - Artifacts Workbook
Definition of Done
Definition	A shared agreement that describes what it means for work to be considered complete.
Purpose	•  Ensures transparency and quality
•  Creates a common understanding of “done”
•  Prevents unfinished or low-quality work from being passed forward


Product Backlog
Definition	An ordered list of everything that might be needed in the product.
Purpose	•  Serves as the single source of work for the Scrum Team
•  Helps guide product development toward business goals

Ordering	•  Items are ordered by value, risk, urgency, and dependencies
•  Highest-value items are placed at the top

Product Backlog  Grooming	•  Ongoing process of reviewing and updating backlog items
•  Includes clarifying requirements, re-ordering items, and estimating effort

Large Items	•  Often called Epics
•  Too big to be completed in a single sprint
•  Must be broken down into smaller items

PBIs	•  Individual items in the product backlog
•  Can be features, enhancements, bugs, or technical work



Sprint Backlog
Definition	A list of Product Backlog Items selected for the sprint, plus a plan to deliver them.
Purpose	•  Provides a clear goal for the sprint
•  Helps the team track progress during the sprint

Source of items	Taken from the top of the Product Backlog
How are items chosen?	•  Selected during Sprint Planning
•  Based on priority and team capacity

What does value
orientation vs. results orientation mean?	•  Value Orientation: Focuses on delivering business value
•  Results Orientation: Focuses on completing tasks regardless of value

Task Board	Visual tool that shows work status (To Do / In Progress / Done)
Sprint Backlog Item	A specific task or piece of work needed to complete a PBI


 Burndown Chart
Purpose	Shows remaining work over time in a sprint
How is it updated?	Updated daily as work is completed
How often is
it used?	Reviewed daily, especially during the Daily Scrum
Significance?	•  Helps identify whether the team is on track
•  Highlights risks early

